subsection.p:
In the momentum chapter we studied collision in detail. We established there that  in every collision , the total momentum after the collision is equal to the total momentum before the collision.

	\left( \vec p_{\text{tot}} \right)_{\text{Before}}  \ \ = \ \ \left( \vec p_{\text{tot}} \right)_{\text{After}}\ \ \ \ \ \text{  (all collisions)}

That is, the momenta of the colliding bodies get redistributed by the internal forces of the colliding bodies such that momentum is  neither generated nor lost.

 To be more specific, consider an arbitrary collision depicted in . If this collision is elastic, we will expect the following two equations to hold true.

				 \amp \vec p_{1,i} + \vec p_{2,i}  = \vec p_{1,f} + \vec p_{2,f} 
				 \amp K_{1,i} + K_{2,i}  = K_{1,f} + K_{2,f}

solution.p:
 (a)
				We use x in horizontal direction and y in vertical direction. The conservation of momentum along the two axes give us the following two equations.

					m\times 2 \amp = m\times u\,\cos\,15^{\circ} + m\times w\,\cos\,10^{\circ} 
					0 \amp = m\times u\,\sin\,15^{\circ} - m\times w\,\sin\,10^{\circ} 

				These simplify to

					  0.966\, u + 0.985\, w \amp = 2 
					  0.259\, u - 0.174\, w \amp = 0 

				Therefore,

					  u \amp  = 0.82 \text{ m/s} 
					  w \amp = 1.22\text{ m/s}
